segments.text: tough to really answer which one was the toughest.
Now, I was wondering about, as director in 56 and 57, were you ever approached by, you must have worked, not approached by, but you must have worked with the builders of the aircraft, didn't you?
Yeah, they sometimes came by and
talked about.
What was your relations with these people?
More as technical representatives in terms of what we thought about various aspects of the airplane and the simulators, too.
Were there certain simulators, too?
Did they build the simulators?
I think simulators
probably built by different people.
Were there certain guidelines?
You're in a position where you could make recommendations to the Pentagon pro or con a certain airplane because of the problems with training, I would imagine.
Is that true?
Yes, we made our recommendations to the training commander, and they made them to the Pentagon.
So did the Air Force set up certain guidelines that you'd have to follow when you talked to these representatives from
the companies?
No.
Usually they were there to tell us about something they had done to fix something that had been a problem, and to get our opinion on different things.
When did we start
When did we start, of course this is a time of nuclear deployment too, and we were having nuclear, our atomic bomb testing.
When did we start deploying nuclear weapons on fighters?
When did we?
We got them in Europe when I was there.
In the 60s.
So that was 60 to 62.
They had them before then, I imagine.
I don't know what that was like.
So we had tactical nuclear weapons then.
Did you ever have any training?
You had nuclear capabilities on these airplanes that you were training your students.
Did you have any training or remember any training, special training,
I must have been new.
No, we had a school area at Randolph that we ran.
It had to do with characteristics.
And I had a course at Sandia.
I had a course at Sandia.
People attended.
On all the, I think all of them had to attend.
All those who were involved with it.
They had to have that orientation course, and they had courses of their own in the organization.
So this was set up before you even got on?
Well, we had a special weapons section in the Crew Training Air Force.
We were responsible for setting up the syllabuses and the curriculum for these courses.
That started a long time before I got it.
So it started a long time before the mid-50s.
Probably started when?
Early 30s?
Early 50s?
At least then.
Maybe even late 40s.
Were there any special problems because of the nuclear deployment?
Well, yes.
You had a high degree of...
You had to have a high degree of training.
People had to be qualified and then they had to display that proficiency.
Sure.
And safety was prime.
It was paramount to everybody.
And you could certainly flunk an ORI or something else if you messed up in any way or any other special way.
What was it?
We had procedures that had to be followed in the letter.
I would imagine.
And everybody was supposed to know.
What about an attack procedure to use a tactical nuclear weapon?

on infantry or tanks or something like that how could an airplane ever move in and drop a low level particular weapon and then escape the blast itself we all we were using him he'd come down and pull up toss it over your shoulder you roll out i see what's known as the shoulder toss i see so he'd come down real low you wouldn't
We wouldn't use a tactical weapon on it, just troops.
No, they'd be on something bigger than that.
Did you practice?
Not practice, but I mean, did you train against ships, like a squadron of ships or something like that?
No.
We had practiced.
We practiced against ships, but I mean, you didn't target them.
Because they make an excellent radar.
Oh, yeah.
Doing it by radar is an excellent target.
Most of the work that I was associated with was for ground targets.
Airfields.
Plants.
See these?
Particular parts of the area.
Radar.
Wow.
After you left that job, you had a rather unusual job as the Air Force Senior Advisor for three years, 57 to 60, in Indiana.
In the Indiana National Guard.
That is an unusual assignment, isn't it?
Or an Air Force colonel?
No.
But I mean for somebody with your background.
They have one in every state.
And this was a fighter wing.
And I was there as advisor to the wing commander and three squadrons.
Advise in what?
advising them on the Air Force policies and procedures.
I had some, I had the Air Force advisor, officer type pilot with each squadron.
And I had the airmen, specialists, and personnel in supply and maintenance.
And we
observed their procedures during their training and advised them on it.
Helped them keep their records right and see if they kept their records right.
All on Air Force procedures.
What did you think was the quality of the National Guard?
Did you form any opinion?
Very impressive.
Really?
Very impressive.
As a matter of fact, they came to Europe right after that and they did a hell of a job.
They came to Europe when
truman i mean not truman kennedy sent sent all those units over there in the 60s they did a real fine job
They really develop a lot of good pilots, well-trained pilots.
And the core of the whole thing are the technicians, which are there all the time and do all the maintenance on the airplanes.
And the other people come in on the weekends and go to camp in the summertime.
And they build up some darn good units.
And they've got a lot of talent, just a lot of talent in the National Guard.
I've often heard from some reserve officers that there's some tension between reserve officers and the Army Reserve, National Guard, et cetera, and the radar.
regular officers.
Did you find any of them?
What's your comment on that?
Well, I think the regular officers tend to look down on the reserves.
It's not being trained.
By and large, the reserves and the National Guard are a lot of them.
I know the National Guard isn't a reserve.
It's probably not as well done as
Might as well train.
Might as well train.
Really?
They don't have it.
The National Guard got double motivation.
They work for the state, too.
Sure.
The state has put up with it.
They won't put up with it.
A lot.
They won't put up with it.
Thank you, thank you, or anything like that.
Okay.
Depends on the state, would you say?
Probably depends on the general state.
I'm sure it's the same.
I guess it would be different in different states.
I've been associated with lots of National Guard organizations.
I've been associated with a number of organizations.
But all of them in Indiana and some of them here in Texas are aware.
Indiana, yes, I investigated an accident.
That's one thing senior advisors does, is to send to investigate the accident of the commander of the 10th Air Force.
It was the 10th.
I don't know where they are now.
And they report back on it.
part of it is looking over the squadron to see what kind of people we got and how they do it and what the procedures are.
I investigated one there in the Dallas Naval Air Station.
There was a National Guard squadron there, a Texas National Guard squadron there,
I don't know what they were flying.
They had an accident on the T-33.
And what did you think of the Texas Air National?
And I also was with them at Ellington and Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, Minnesota.
all those National Guard units on committee.
And they're all good organizations.
I've heard from some that there's more politics in the National Guard than in regular service.
What's your opinion of that?
That's probably true.
Is that decreased efficiency, or did you have any problems with that?
Any problems that you had to deal with directly in Indiana?
No, there were no problems there.
Politics is an adjunct general, who the adjunct general is.
Sure.
I guess getting to be appointed, you have to know the head of the general.
But as far as the officers that you met in the Air National Guard, you found them of what type of quality?
High quality.
High quality.
High quality.
High caliber people.
Let's move on then.
They spent the next four years in Germany.
I spent two years with the 86th Air Division, which you grew out of the 86th Fighter Interceptor.
It's Swineford.
Mm-hmm.
Oh, so it was her reunion.
Well, not really.
I was director of operations for two years, and we phased out the F-86B and phased in the F-102 for our interceptors.
And we also had the radar squadron.
We found an operations center.
Did you have any dealings during these four years?
Did you deal with NATO?
Well, we had a German liaison officer on staff.
And so did you go out on maneuvers with other NATO air forces?
Well, we participated in joint exercises, NATO exercises, yes.
Q And what were your feelings about NATO and its ability to defend Western Europe?
A Well, I thought Air Force-wise, we had a pretty good organization.
I didn't know about the ground troops.
At that time, we had tactical nuclear missiles, too.
When did we develop those?
They were there.
When did we develop those?
When did we develop them?
In the 40s, late 40s.
So these were air-to-air?
No, they were air-to-ground.
Okay, air-to-ground.
It's a Matador missile, I think.
Matador, yeah.
We hit them.
They were under us, too.
And so you were training with those missiles, basically?
Yes.
Director of Operations, what were your duties there?
I had charge of all the flying and training.
Combat crew evaluation, tactical evaluation, we had a tactical evaluation team.
And we were responsible for all the training programs and all the crew training programs and so forth.
and all the operations.
You didn't get to fly yourself, did you?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, you didn't?
Sure did.
What type of flight?
Yeah, 102.
Great.
I checked out.
I flew them.
A lot of them exercised.
So I bet you that was kind of nice to get back in the driver's seat.
It was.
Well, I flew with the National Guard.
I flew just like every other pilot.
Really?
I flew their full missions.
I flew with them on every type of mission they had.
When they went on maneuvers, I went with them and flew with them.
Qualified combat ready just the same as every pilot in there.
I qualified combat ready in 102, too.
Okay.
Wow.
How about...
Do you think that the Air National Guard when you were in Indiana, do you think that they were, I mean, did they qualify combat readiness?
I'm sure they did.
I had to say that was one of my jobs to see that they did and see that they had the program to do it.
We had a range of our own down below Indianapolis.
We dropped bombs and scraped and did everything that was required to fill this attorney.
And, well, that's quite an accomplishment, isn't it, to get National Guard or Reserve troops combat ready?
Sure is.
And we have tactical evaluation.
The team come in and evaluate it.
I mean, fast.
So, that is an accomplishment.
Isn't it true that, I don't know about most, but large amounts of our Reserve troops are not combat ready?
for one reason or the other.
Yes, I think that's true.
Very stable.
Why'd you become the vice commander?
That was a promotion, wasn't it?
Yes.
The commander of the Air Force, 17th Air Force, just told me he was going to send me up there to be the vice commander.
I said, yes, sir.
I'll be happy to go.
That was the F-105.
And did you get to fly that, too?
Oh, yeah.
I had to.
I don't think the boss man would let me stay there if I hadn't.
But you wanted to do that anyway.
Oh, yeah.
What was your job there?
Vice Commander.
Well, I know, but what did you do as a Vice Commander?
And how large was the command?
Well, it was a wing base.
I'd say 3,000 people.
How many airplanes?
We had 75, 75 radios on that category.
I assisted the commander and he started his responsibilities.
I did whatever he wanted me to do.
some of the things he turned over me to do, but to mark a training program, to handle a lot of disciplinary matters, court-martials.
Did you have any discipline or anything like that?
No.
Did troops get along well with the Germans?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, the Germans.
We had a good relationship with the locals.
We had tennis matches with them.
No kidding?
Yeah.
Soccer teams.
We invite them to our football games.
He had me do a lot of letter writing and things like that.
Who was a commander?
I had two different ones.
He was later a brigadier general.
The second one's name was Blood.
Blood?
Was he a cold-blooded guy?
No, he was a nice guy.
He retired down in Austin.
I was wondering about this time that France was en route to get out of NATO.
Yeah, that was getting pretty hairy.
How so, and how did that affect you people?

Oh, the NATO language was supposed to be English, and the French controller started talking French, and they made it very difficult to get a clearance to fly with France, so we more or less stayed away from France.
Well, we did fly over there.
We did fly over there.
It got pretty sticky.
Were there negative feelings toward the French?
Yes.
Do you remember any incidents or episodes?
No, not to bring up any incidents or episodes.
It just was a general feeling against them.
And did it, now of course they were moving things out of France and into Germany.
Did that have any impact on your air base?
Yeah.
How?
Well, not on our air base.
Some of them had moved.
Ramstein must have had a big increase.
Yeah.
Well, that was at Midburg.
Yeah, right.
Oh.
We did
have some of the guys go back to France and go by and see some people that they had known and said the people told them that this wasn't what the French people wanted, it's what they'd all wanted.
And it had nothing to do with their feelings against the Americans.
And these are some people that had been stationed in one of the bases that had to move.
and going back to see their friends in France.
What was the general attitude of the Air Force toward the French in this behavior?
Well, it was a gentle, gentle feeling of disgust and awe.
not necessarily the French people themselves.
And we started calling them Air France, Air Chance.
They couldn't be dependent upon us.
That's right.
That's good.
Well, you have to leave Germany.
You were there for four years.
I suppose your wife was with you, wasn't she?
Yeah, my wife and children.
And they were in American schools.
Were you eager to get back to the United States after four years?
Well, I wasn't particularly eager to come back to the job that I was in.
Yeah, Commandant of?
Squadron Officer School.
Of the what?
Squadron Officer School.
Okay, Squadron Officer School.
at the Air University, so you're back in education again.
Yeah.
And this is a position of responsibility.
How many students are at that school a year?
Something over 2,000.
We have 703 classes of 750.
And how long does the course run?
I didn't think I'd ever get that number.
About 12 weeks.
12 weeks.
Now, what was the aim of the school?
Well, the purpose was to qualify the young officers to be Spartan-level staff officers
How did you do that?
Well, we gave them a very thorough academic course, and then we put them in practical problems, and they were all divided into seminars, and the seminars worked as a group to solve the problems.
And each seminar, each little group, each section had its faculty member in it.
We divided them up based on their backgrounds, so we would get a completely heterogeneous background together.
They weren't homogenous.
Sure.
Everybody had their ideas.
This guy did the SAC, and this would be the MAC, and this guy.
We broke up the section by computer and assigned them that way.
What did you think was the quality of that school?
I thought it was outstanding.
It was outstanding when I got there.
Did you improve it?
I mean, was there anything that you could do?
The only thing that I could do was try to preserve the standard that we had and select people.
We'd select instructors from the people going through, and we had very high standards.
To qualify to be an instructor at Squadron Officer School was a real honor.
They were highly motivated and really gung-ho.
What rank were most of the instructors?
First lieutenants and captains.
We had students who were second lieutenants and first lieutenants?
First lieutenants.
They were basically all first lieutenants?
First lieutenants, you might have a captain or two.
Kirstie Townsend, less than seven years service.
Were they all career-oriented officers?
Um, yeah.
How did you maintain those high standards besides picking top notch instructors when vacancies occurred?
Well, the organization had a real high esprit de corps, and we critiqued everything before we put it on.
We made sure it was what we wanted before we put it on.
And even every lecture that I gave was rehearsed and critiqued before we put it on.
And they don't mind shooting, punching punches at you.
At the boss.
At the boss, and tell him
All due respect, sir, but... We had one old retired civilian professor that was real good at that, too.
Everybody participated in everything.
We even had the athletic board.
We had a hell of an athletic board.
I was assigned to a section, and I competed in that section and all that too.
No kidding?
All the families there, after we'd finish our sports, we'd have all the families there for kicking.
What type of athletics?
Well, we played soccer, flicker ball, you know what flicker ball is?
It's a little longer than basketball courts.
We played with basketball back boys in football.
You can't run with the ball, you have to pass it.
Is that the one where you run three steps and have to throw it?
Yeah, hit the board, flicker ball.
Soccer, flicker ball.
And you participated with all of your... Volleyball, volleyball.
But basically, it was your aim then, just to maintain those high standards.
Well, improve them if we could, but... Well, was there any way you could improve them?
No.
Then did you improve them?
I don't know whether we did or not, but we tried to.
What specifically did you try to improve, do you remember?
Well, we took suggestions from the students and staffed them, and if they looked good, we implemented them.
We did make some changes.
So there was a good relationship between instructors and students.
Oh, yeah.
They're just like...
It was a very close relationship, and over each there were two different wings, and then there was competition between the wings.
We started several new programs, but I don't remember specifically what they were right now.
Now, at this time, at this time, of course, the warrant is really increasing.
You'll hear 1964, 65, 66, especially 65 and 66, the big buildup.
And here you are at Maxwell Air Force Base.
I was wondering if you applied for service.
Did you want to go to Vietnam?
Oh, I sure did.
Did you apply?
No, I had no way of applying.
Well, I mean, did you volunteer?
Did you write a letter?
Did you have somebody that you could?
No, I didn't have somebody I could write to.
I could have, but I didn't.
I didn't write a letter at that time.
I figured that I had a good chance of going there as soon as I finished my tour, but I wasn't.
No, so what happened here in July 1967 to September 1967, here you're sent off to the Azores.
You're the commander of the U.S. forces in the Azores, but at the same time you get a promotion.
Tell me how, what happened on, how'd you first learn the fact that you were going to be promoted to a general officer?
Um, my boss told me.
The commander there in the university.
Told me I was going to do this.
Well, what'd you say?
I said, thank you, sir.
Told him that was great.
Did you think that you were going to make it to generals?
Not at that time.
Why not?
Well, I just didn't know whether I'd had enough experience to warrant promotion.
The way you get promoted, you've got to get on the major commander's list before you even get submitted.
And then after you get there, well, that's it.
a promotion board and makes a decision.
Probably 6,000 colonels or however many they're going to promote.
So your chances are not always good.
I just happened to have my commander on the platform.
Who was that commander?
General Parkinson.
Carpenter at the University of, he was the commander of the area.
And you think that's the main reason you received that promotion?
Because of his influence?
Yes.
Was he his research?
Yes.
Did they give you a certain, did they tell you about how you were supposed to act when you became the general?
No.
After I got my assignment, I was made a brevet general, a brigadier general, because the commander of the Portuguese Air Force in the Azores was a brigadier general.
And my promotion wasn't due until after I was reported in, so I pinned on my stars before I got promoted.
I got promoted, but I didn't get paid.
I'll put it that way.
I got promoted, but I didn't get paid until later.
And so that was when you arrived in the Azars, you'd be on the same level as the commander of the Portuguese Air Force.
Tell me about that job in the Azars.
How large was our force at that time?
Our force was not particularly dark at that time.
It was a command, a joint command under St. Glam.
And it was a joint command, Army, Navy, Air Force command, for the Azores, which was mainly lodges, airbases.
The Air Force organization was a wing, was an air base wing under Military Airlift Command.
As such, I reported to the commander of the 21st Air Force in New Jersey, which is a subcommand of Military Airlift Command.
But as a Joint Commander, I reported to the Joint Chief of Land.
And this Air Base Wing maintained the base and serviced all the airplanes, maintained the airplanes that came through.
We had assigned to us a C-54.
That's the only airplane we had.
No kidding.
This must have been mostly a diplomatic job.
But the Navy had a squadron there of anti-sub warfare, so they didn't fly.
And the Army maintained the rescue boats.
What did the Air Force do?
The Air Force took care of them on the ground.
Took care of their one plane?
No, it took care of everybody.
Oh, it took care of everybody's plane on the ground.
We didn't take care of the Navy's planes that were there, because they had their own squadron and maintenance hangar, and all the transit airplanes.
See, it's a transit business.
The American Air Lift Command and the Motor Air Lift Command came through there daily, hauling supplies, different people, different places.
But it was a very unusual command, because the Army had all the boats, and the Navy had all the airplanes,
And we took care of everybody on the ground and protected them.
We had the Air Police.
We had the large... And you were in charge of... You were the senior officer in charge of all of them, right?
In charge of all of them.
And also the liaison with the ambassador to Portugal, the chief of staff of the Portuguese Air Force.
And I went to Lisbon.
About once a month.
Really?
To see the Secretary of the Air Force, to see the Ambassador.
To see our Ambassador?
Yeah, our Ambassador.
Who was he at the time?
Ambassador Bennett.
How did you get along with the State Department people?
Just great.
We had a very pleasant relationship.
I got along well with the consul to the Azores.
Military governor of the Azores.
I had to go over to see him.
He was on another island and so was I.
He was on the same island as the consul was.
We had a very close relationship.
And it was a real good working relationship.
We had civilian programs that we were hanging on to with the local Missouri and, you know, the island we were on.
What type of civilian programs?
We were getting semen for them.
It was a people-to-people program that Eisenhower set up.
People-to-people program.
Semen for improving the stock.
Sterile med flies to help eradicate them.
You know, different programs like that.
And we entertained the Portuguese, all the Portuguese hierarchy.
They entertained us.
It was more a diplomatic job.
You're absolutely right.
How'd you like that?
How'd you like being a diplomat instead of a...
It was pretty challenging, I'll tell you.
It was a pretty challenging job.
only had one bad thing happen.
Well, the Portuguese had a club on the beach, and we had some black people.
And we were allowed to go out there and participate in it.
And these blacks
came in while the...
Were they Americans?
Yeah, black Americans, servicemen.
Came in on this, uh, broke in, uh, busted in on the end of this club, which had been reserved that night for a party by Portuguese officers.
And they were, they had altercations in place.
That was, that was really bad.
Well, what happened?
They started fighting?
Well, they had a little fight, and they left.
And they were under your command?
Yeah, they were under my command.
The blacks were under your command?
Yeah, the blacks were under my command.
I wasn't going to go out and attack them.
How'd you handle them?
I consulted my boss.
after it happened, and he sent me some assistance.
A lawyer who had handled similar cases and was a great assistance, by the way, when he got there.
I restricted the airmen to the base, and then
discussed the matter with the senior Portuguese commander and put my head in my hand and went to see the head of the Air Force, the Portuguese Air Force, and told him that
We would handle it in a way that is pleasing to him.
